<TEXT>
the murderous bombardment in beirut the 
worst in four years has squeezed peoples daily lives to four 
hours of scurrying about their business and 20 hours underground 
when syrian and christian artillery gunners rest at daybreak 
thousands of trapped residents cautiously emerge from bunkers 
their first order of business is to hurriedly buy fresh supplies 
of food water candles gas lamps decks of cards and sleeping 
pills 
just before the antagonists resume the deadly duel that began 
three weeks ago they rush back to shelters on both sides of the 
green line that divides the city into moslem and christian sectors 
most nightclubs bars restaurants cafes and movie houses are 
closed so are schools and universities banks operate haphazardly 
for two or three hours a day depending on the ferocity of the 
shelling 
the only thing that matters nowadays is selfpreservation 
said amin trad a pharmacist in christian east beiruts ashrafiyeh 
district survival is the name of the game 
he did not recall a similar stampede for sleeping pills in 
lebanons 14year civil war 
i dont have statistics but if this continues we will soon 
run out of tranquilizers said trad whose pharmacy is shielded 
by tall sandbag walls 
there are no severe shortages at present wholesalers try to 
monopolize goods in order to raise prices and stores order new 
stock during lulls in the fighting 
some residents manage to joke about the shelling 
tell my friends in west beirut not to worry about me said 
bahjat jaber a police reporter who lives in east beiruts 
maameltein suburb like many others he commuted between beiruts 
two sectors before the latest round of fighting 
i have all the fireworks some 200 shells explode around my 
apartment nightly the house is always shaking like a swing and i 
