<TEXT>
smoking makes the body burn more calories 
according to a study that helps explain one of lifes biological 
injustices why people put on weight when they give up cigarettes 
the research publi care of about 100 calories a day for the 
typical smoker 
smokers typically weigh five to 10 pounds less than nonsmokers 
and they usually put on that much weight when they break the habit 
the question has been why this happens 
part of the reason is that folks often eat more when they stop 
smoking and some studies have shown they are more likely to crave 
sugar while preliminary evidence suggested that they also burned 
calories more slowly many experts thought this effect was small 
in the past scientists have studied this by watching changes in 
metabolism when people smoke while sitting still in the lastest 
work researchers decided to see what happened to metabolism when 
people smoked while moving around just as they do in real lifeought it 
was conceivable we wouldnt see any effect 
said dr kenneth a perkins who directed the universityrgh school of medicine 
study thats published in the new 
england journal of medicine 
to our surprise whe opposite that it was much more 
enhanced it reversed our thinking the implication is that the 
metabolic eing is much more important than everyone 
else has considered when staying ng increases metabolism by about 5 
percent but it raises it by about 12 
percent among other things this could help explain hy some 
people balloon when they quit cigaretteothers manage to 
hold their weight steady 
if people tenn coffee breaks 
or while relaxing at home watching tv they wont gain as much 
weight when they quit said perkins those who smoke while 
active are likely to be thinnero begin with because of their 
smoking so they risk putting on more when they stop smoking 
nancy a rigotti of harvard 
noted that some people especiall keep smoking because they 
are afraid of gaining weight 
until our cultural obsession wih slenderness abates she 
wrote we must pay more attention to the way weight gain impedes 
