polling places across the nation would close 
at a uniform time in presidential elections under a plan on its way 
to the senate after winning house approval 
the bill approved 238154 on wednesday is designed to reduce 
the effect of outcome projections made hours before the polls close 
in the wet and in some lateclosing states elsewhere 
the importance of western votes for president is being 
diminished just because of where we live rep ron wyden dore 
declared 
the measure has passed the house twice before only to languish 
in the senate but lawmakers say senate prospects are better this 
year 
the bill calls for closing times of 9 pm est 8 pm cst and 7 
pm mst in presidential election years only the switch from 
daylightsaving time to standard time in the pacific time zone 
would be postponed a maximum of two weeks polls there would close 
at 7 pm pdt 
under the timetable polling places would shut their doors 
simultaneously making it impossible for results from some states 
to indicate a winner and influence turnout elsewhere 
only presidential years would be covered by the bill which 
would take effect in 1992 and would not apply to alaska and hawaii 
the plan is designed to dovetail with a 1985 agreement under 
which major television networks said they would voluntarily refrain 
from projecting election results within a state until the polls 
close there 
it is unclear if local races are actually affected by early 
projections house rules committee chairman claude pepper dfla 
however said tuesday that he believed the phenomenon may have 
contributed to the 1980 defeat of rep al ullman dore then 
chairman of the ways and means committee 
either way lawmakers say voter frustration because of such 
projections is basically unhealthy 
