<TEXT>
in an antiextinction effort a 
state legislature has enacted a law under which anyone caught with 
the eggs of leatherback turtles can be fined up to 363 or 
sentenced to six months in jail 
many malaysians eat the eggs as a delicacy believing they 
increase sexual prowess 
the law passed wednesday by the trengganu state assembly in 
kuala trengganu 180 miles northeast of kuala lumpur says the only 
lawful purpose for keeping the eggs is for hatching by the state 
fisheries department 
abdul rashid ngah chairman of the state fisheries and 
agriculture committee said he proposed the law because the number 
of leatherback turtles laying eggs in rantau abang near kuala 
trengganu had declined to about 500 in recent years and measures 
were needed to prevent their extinction 
the turtles measuring as much as five feet in diameter and 
weighing up to 900 pounds range the seas as far as japan the 
philippines and australia but return to the beaches of rantau abang 
each june to august to lay their eggs 
scientists say the turtles which live as long as 100 years 
return each year to the exact beach where they were born to lay up 
to 70 eggs 
