<TEXT>
almost 30 years ago a young australian 
who loved american country music died in a car accident in sydney 
leaving behind 2000 old 78s and boxes of correspondence with the 
pioneers who had made the records 
john edwards never made it to america but his collection did 
as he directed in his will his legacy forms the nucleus of the 
southern folklife collection that opened this week at the 
university of north carolina at chapel hill 
in the past 20 years historians have begun to look more and 
more toward folklife materials said mike casey an archivist of 
the collection theyre looking to sound recordings to provide a 
perspective on on the history of the south 
in 1983 unc bought the edwards collection from the university 
of california at los angeles where it had been greatly expanded by 
acquisitions of more recordings and documents unc combined the 
purchase with the unc folklore archives to form the southern 
folklife collection 
with 38000 items dating to 1906 the collection is being touted 
as one of the nations three top resources for country music 
research joining the country music foundation in nashville tenn 
and the library of congress 
music is highly symbolic said dan patterson chairman of 
the folklore curriculum at unc it encodes deep statements about 
your identity it speaks of values that are woven into your life 
the collection includes gospel spirituals blues bluegrass 
cajun ballads native american string band and country music 
everything from sermons recorded at a primitive baptist church to 
the skillet lickers recording of the fiddle tune cottoneyed 
joe to merle travis im sick and tired of you little 
darling 
researchers musicians and other visitors also have access to 
books videotapes and scrapbooks booths are available for 
listening to the tapes and theres a sound studio to erase many of 
the flaws on old recordings 
the people who have gathered in chapel hill through saturday to 
mark the opening of the collection include musicians and the 
researchers and music professionals who have documented their lives 
a concert friday night will feature performers such as etta 
baker a blues guitarist wade mainer who in the 1920s was one of 
the first stars of country music and esteban jordan a texan who 
calls himself the jimi hendrix of the accordion 
another scheduled proformer is y ngong knul a 67yearold from 
cambodia now living in greensboro who performs a ritualized form of 
chanting he symbolizes a musical direction that may be part of the 
traditional southern music of tomorrow 
theres starting to be a number of new ethnic groups moving 
into the south who have not been recorded as of yet casey said 
theyre hispanic and theyre vietnamese and theyre playing 
their music 
its clearly not what what weve consider southern traditional 
music up till now he said but the fact is in the next 100 
years it will be and its important to document it 
