<TEXT>
americans took out 422 billion more in 
consumer debt than they paid off in february the slowest pace of 
growth in four months the government said thursday in a report 
consistent with other signs the economy may be slowing 
the federal reserve said the february increase in consumer 
credit was down slightly from januarys rise of 437 billion and 
was the smallest monthly gain since a 391 billion increase in 
october 
growth in the category of debt that includes credit cards 
strengthened in february while the gain in auto loans was slightly 
smaller than in january borrowing through bank and credit union 
loans not secured by real estate also slowed while mobile home 
lending declined 
analysts said the restrained growth in debt indicates consumers 
may be becoming more cautious about their buying plans and is in 
line with other signs that the economy is slowing down in the 
seventh year of its record peacetime expansion 
it doesnt suggest any great retrenchment by consumers but it 
does indicate somewhat more caution said economist cynthia latta 
of data resources inc in lexington mass its consistent with 
this gradually accumulating evidence that the economy is beginning 
to cool off 
consumer spending is closely watched as a barometer of economic 
health because it accounts for twothirds of economic activity 
most government reports on the economys performance in february 
pointed downward although 1989 began with strong momentum 
analysts expect the economy to slow this year as the recovery 
ages and the nation responds to a yearlong campaign by the federal 
reserve board to push up interest rates to restrain growth and keep 
inflation in check 
februarys 75 percent rise in the seasonally adjusted annual 
rate of credit growth was down from 79 percent in january and 78 
percent in december for all of 1988 consumer debt rose 875 
percent 
auto loans rose 21 billion in february an 86 percent annual 
rate of growth following a 213 billion increase during january 
automobile sales have been weak this year with business held 
down by rising interest rates automakers in recent weeks have 
launched a new round of cash rebates and lowinterest financing 
programs in an effort to boost sales and avoid large production 
cutbacks 
growth in the category of debt that includes credit cards rose 
16 billion in february a 103 percent annual rate of growth 
that followed a january increase of 102 billion a 66 percent 
annual rate 
mobile home debts dropped 59 million in february a 28 percent 
rate of decline after rising 50 million in january 
bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate rose by 
569 million in february a 41 percent rate of growth after 
rising 117 billion in january 
the various changes left total consumer debt at a seasonally 
adjusted 67478 billion in february up 81 percent from a year 
earlier 
