<TEXT>
doctors have discovered how to identify genetic 
defects in embryos as young as two days old greatly reducing the 
need for aborting a abnormal fetus in later stages of pregnancy 
researchers said thursday 
it is a wonderful move forward a scientific advance a 
medical advance and an ethical advance biologist robert edwards 
told doctors from 42 nations at a conference on the test tube 
fertilization techniques 
the new work by british and american scientists has developed 
screening techniques for sexlinked handicaps such as muscular 
dystrophy as well as some immunodeficiency and neurological 
disorders 
it has preciptated the opening later this year of the first 
genetic screening programs using in vitro fertilization 
they will be at britains bourne hallan clinic in cambridge and 
hammersmith hospital in london said edwards a member of the 
british team responsible for the worlds first test tube baby in 
1978 
the traditional screening method amniocentesis can be 
performed only in the second trimester of pregnancy it involves 
removing a small amount of amniotic fluid surrounding the fetus in 
the uterus 
if a genetic disorder is found the woman faces the often 
traumatic choice of abortion in the fifth or sixth month of 
pregnancy 
some women never get over a lost baby especially when an 
abortion is performed after amniocentesis when she has already 
felt it move and is heavily pregnant said dr robert m winston 
of hammersmith hospital 
the new method allows doctors to study the genetic makeup of a 
2dayold embryo produced in a test tube 
by removing a single cell of the embryo then amplifying and 
copying specific gene sequences scientists can identify defects 
if the embryo is normal it is implanted in the womans uterus 24 
hours later 
now youre seeing the breakthrough youve got the embryo 
right before you put it in so they will know their pregnancy is 
right that for me is marvelous said roberts 
among drawbacks is the low success rate of only one in five for 
test tube fertilizations 
roberts also cautioned the new method would not immediately 
eliminate the need for amniocentesis 
in the early days of the work wed have to do amniocentesis 
to find out what our failure rate is edwards explained we 
take an embryo and type it then you type it with amniocentesis 
and say yes its a male and its free of disease 
but he added even if youre only 95 percent right you reduce 
the amniocentesis abortions to just 5 percent of what weve got 
now 
among disorders the new technique can detect are absence of 
enzymes which lead to muscular dystrophy and a highly debilitating 
disease known as lesch nyhan both of which affect males children 
with lesch nyhan are crippled and have to be restrained phsyically 
to prevent them mutilating themselves 
a woman who carries a dominant gene for such inherited disorders 
has a 50 percent chance of passing on the defect while a woman 
with a recessive gene has one in four chances of passing it on 
winston cited one woman who produced a child with lesch nyhan 
then had five lateterm abortions when amniocentesis detected the 
disorder 
he said another womans first marriage ended after two abortions 
of fetuses suffering muscular dystrophy the woman since has 
aborted three more such fetuses 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

