<TEXT>
consumers prefer less fat in their steaks and 
hamburger and the beef industry has responded well to those 
demands two texas aampm university scientists said thursday 
h russell cross and jeff savell said further progress can be 
expected in the future as attention continues to be drawn to health 
issues notably the dietary linkage between fats and high levels of 
blood cholesterol 
but savell told a conference sponsored by the national 
cattlemens association that if he had to send cattle producers and 
the beef industry a note from the teacher it might say 
excellent progress made in making product fit consumers needs 
keep working on leanness convenience and cost value remember to 
maintain taste or consumers will go elsewhere 
the beef industry drew praise from jay fletcher of the community 
nutrition institute who agreed that less fat is being sold to 
consumers 
i think they have done more than many other industries to 
recognize the dangers of excessive fat consumption and take steps 
to inform consumers about that fletcher said in a telephone 
interview 
