industry wants to recover its market share they have lost it 
steadily to chicken and poultry in general over the past 10 years 
fletcher said that occurred largely because of consumer 
perception of beef as a highfat food 
it was just a year ago that the agriculture department released 
a study by texas aampm led by cross and savell that showed the 
trimmable fat on retail cuts of beef had been reduced 27 percent in 
two years 
the 45000 study paid for by the beef industry and usda 
showed that the average thickness of fat on steaks and roasts from 
primal cuts or the major wholesale cuts of beef was 014 inch 
while the average for all cuts from chuck roast to stew meat was 
011 inch or less than oneeighth of an inch 
most retailers have been using a quarterinch beef fat trim or 
less since 1985 compared with a standard of half an inch before 
that according to the industry 
at the conference cross said consumers have indicated they 
would pay for more closely trimmed beef preferably with external 
fat of less than oneeighth inch 
internal fat or marbling has been a factor in the taste of 
beef and cross said this still is important to consumers the 
challenge he said is take fat off not out of beef 
cross said that texas aampm meat scientists are currently working 
with human medicine researchers at baylor college of medicine and 
the university of texas southwestern medical center on projects 
aimed at further improvements in the healthfulness of beef 
the work includes modification of the fatty acid content of meat 
product through changes in cattle feeds and products themselves 
fatty acids can potentially elevate cholesterol levels in human 
blood but cross said that even now only 27 percent of the total 
fat in beef is the type of saturated fatty acid that can raise 
cholesterol 
savell told of recent research on the composition of cooked as 
well as raw beef with reduced or no external fat for example if a 
slice of beef with all the fat trimmed off is cooked the fat 
content of the interior meat is reduced by 20 percent from a slice 
with a quarterinch layer of fat 
that is because less fat migrates from the outside into the meat 
tissue 
when you trim the fat off a steak that has a half inch of fat 
you get rid of half the total cholesterol savell said 
