<TEXT>
the air force said thursday the inflight loss 
of escape hatches on two b1b bombers would lead to more frequent 
inspections of the equipment in the future but the problem had not 
stalled the return of the bombers to the air 
col larry greer an air force spokesman said 60 of the 97 
b1bs in the fleet had been cleared for air operations by late 
thursday and that all of the b1bs scheduled for training flights 
thursday or thursday night would be permitted to fly 
the b1b fleet has been slowly returning to the air this week 
after being grounded in the wake of a march 27 incident at dyess 
air force base texas that incident involved the failure of gears 
that move the wings on the swingwing bomber 
as that grounding order was being lifted this week two b1bs 
experienced unusual problems with the same escape hatch suddenly 
blowing off during training flights 
the first hatchblowing incident occurred about 11 am tuesday 
as the jet was climbing from a lowaltitude exercise near the 
texasnew mexico border the 3foot by 4foot hatch blew off at 
about 12500 feet 
then at about 1145 am wednesday a hatch in the same place on 
another b1b blew off at about 19000 feet as the jet flew over la 
junta training range near pueblo colo 
no one was injured and both airplanes made routine landings but 
the incidents caused the air force to order another inspection of 
each plane before they took off on training flights 
greer said thursday the air force had not recovered either of 
the two hatches but that inspections of the other planes in the 
fleet suggested routine opening and closing of the hatches during 
maintenance can gradually throw the locking latches beyond normal 
tolerance levels 
were going to perform the inspection on these hatches more 
often greer said its part of the growing process with a new 
plane as equipment matures you have to adjust your maintenance 
and inspection schedules 
the spokesman added technicians also had discovered that by 
painting a small stripe across the hatch inside the plane it was 
possible to provide an easy visual cue to the crew to make sure a 
hatch is shut tight 
as for the problem that prompted the grounding greer said that 
87 b1bs had undergone the required inspection by thursday and 60 
had been cleared for flight 
ten are awaiting inspection in the case of the other 27 he 
continued a gear box that handles drive shafts that help to move 
the wings has been removed and shipped to the sundstrand corp the 
maker for inspection 
the spokesman declined to predict when the entire fleet would be 
back in the air 
