<TEXT>
a majority of telephone users think the seven 
regional bell companies should be allowed to enter the equipment 
manufacturing longdistance and information services markets 
according to a survey released thursday by the telephone companies 
in the random survey of 24291 registered voters 58 percent 
agreed that congress this year should consider lifting the 
restrictions placed on the bell companies in the 1984 breakup of 
american telephone amp telegraph co 
in the atampt breakup the regional phone companies were 
prohibited from entering the phone equipment research development 
and manufacturing business and from providing their own 
longdistance and information services to local and national 
customers 
the us district court in washington reaffirmed those 
prohibitions last year saying the bell companies if freed from 
their restraints might engage in predatory pricing and 
crosssubsidization of services and discriminate against 
competitors wanting to use their phone lines 
the court did allow the regional companies to provide 
gateway services through which users can call a single 800 
number to gain access to a variety of services such as compuserve 
and the source databases 
ed reilly president of kennan research of new york city said 
his companys survey found that americans want american companies 
freed to compete in providing telecommunications products and 
services consumers want as many choices as possible 
according to kennan 
74 percent of those surveyed said the seven bell companies 
should be allowed to compete in the longdistance arena 
78 percent thought those companies should be allowed to offer 
information services which could include electronic banking 
health monitoring home security services and data bases 
79 percent said the bell companies should be allowed to 
research develop and manufacture telephone equipment 
68 percent said the newspaper advertising business does not 
need to be protected from electronic yellow pages that the bell 
companies could offer 
74 percent said allowing the seven companies to compete in the 
telephone equipment market would strengthen us competitiveness 
against overseas manufacturers of high technology equipment 
atampt spokesman herb linnen said those surveyed werent told 
there is already stiff and growing competition for atampt in 
manufacturing equipment 
atampt chairman robert allen said in a recent speech in washington 
that the bell companies if allowed to begin manufacturing might 
be inclined to team with overseas manufacturers to avoid huge 
development costs to the detriment of american workers 
linnen also said atampt never has opposed the bell companies 
entry into the information services business 
the survey was conducted by telephone from november through 
january it had a margin of error of less than 1 percent kennan 
said 
it was commissioned by ameritech bell atlantic bellsouth 
nynex pacific telesis southwestern bell and us west these 
companies operate 22 local telephone companies 
</TEXT>
