<TEXT>
the critics call it drift and maybe theyre 
right but there certainly is a prevailing current in the early 
course of the bush administration and it leads away from some of 
the policies and positions bequeathed by ronald reagan 
president bush has made those moves carefully and quietly item 
by item he is putting his imprint on major programs supplanting 
and in some cases undoing reagan policies transformations that 
have been taking place with scant notice and only a few complaints 
from conservatives 
thats just fine with the white house bush and his lieutenants 
need no trouble on the republican right where the president never 
was a favorite most of the criticism has been coming from other 
directions much of it from democrats 
still there are some ripples on the right when republican 
national chairman lee atwater spoke at the heritage foundation the 
other night one man complained that bush has moved away from some 
favored conservative positions since the election 
george bush is a conservative atwater replied he said on 
two paramount issues opposition to new taxes and a hard line 
against communism bush is solid and absolute he remains hard 
core on both of those the gop chairman said 
bush denies that his administration is adrift challenging those 
who complain about the pace of administration action he said in 
houston last month 
in this kind of work more is going on than meets the eye or 
makes the headlines the proof will come when we look back from the 
year 2000 
hes also countered by joking about the criticism people say 
im indecisive he said last week presidential pause i dont 
know about that 
some started saying that the white house didnt have an 
agenda said vice president dan quayle we have an agenda its 
just that when ronald reagan left he took it with him 
jokes aside if reagan came back he may not recognize some of 
that agenda 
white house press secretary marlin fitzwater who served both 
men says the reagantobush revisions are in approach not in 
goals he says they differ at the margin not on the basics 
from the outset bush has said he envisioned no radical change 
in course from the administration he served as vice president 
nevertheless some reagan positions have been retired since he 
did 
bushs agreement with the democrats on aid to the nicaraguan 
contra rebels is a prime example the administration has agreed to 
seek only nonmilitary aid only through next february and subject 
to congressional committee veto since congress has rejected 
military aid the net result is similar to what reagan got but 
administration policy now is to seek diplomatic answers in central 
america rather than look to military ones 
secretary of state james a baker iii who negotiated the deal 
with congress acknowledged the failure of reagan policy we all 
have to admit that the policy failed to some extent because we were 
not united he said we had an executive branch going in one 
direction and a congress going in the other 
on the domestic agenda the bush administration has embraced a 
compromise version of a bill which reagan pocket vetoed to 
protect federal employees who blow the whistle on waste abuse and 
mismanagement the compromise might have satisfied reagan he never 
said 
the reagan administration opposed any increase in the 335 
hourly minimum wage the bush administration has endorsed an 
increase tied to a lowerthanminimum training wage for new 
workers congressional democrats want a higher minimum and a more 
restricted training wage thats still in dispute and the 
administration has talked of a veto unless there is a satisfactory 
compromise 
bush also has moved away from the reagan position on the 
question of gun controls which also was his own a flat no the 
administration on wednesday widened its import ban on foreignmade 
assault rifles and an official said it is considering a proposal 
that gun buyers register such weapons 
even those modest moves drew the standard protests from the gun 
lobby despite the growing sense of crisis over drugrelated 
violence in american cities and the murder of five children in a 
stockton calif schoolyard 
atwater told his conservative audience that bush remains opposed 
to gun control despite the moves against assault rifles on which 
he said there is growing public sentiment in favor of limits 
if the conservative position is proassault rifle youd 
better get out and start moving around to hear the public outcry 
atwater said 
