spill the state will toughen its environmental laws provide more 
money to monitor compliance with those laws and demand more proof 
of environmental safeguards 
lawmakers already have jumped on the new antioil bandwagon 
legislation introduced tuesday in the senate would tax oil 
companies to pay for protection of state land against spills and 
what appeared to be a losing campaign by cowper to increase the 
states oilproduction tax has new life 
the fallout from the valdez spill also may dampen development 
overall in what has always been a prodevelopment state one that 
bills itself as the last frontier 
i think the development spirit in alaska is going to be much 
more cautious than before the oil spill kelly said 
