rear brake lights and other safety features for pickup trucks and 
minivans a fastgrowing market in addition the agency would have 
to require manufacturers to produce bumpers that can prevent major 
damage to a car traveling at 5 mph 
the reagan administration had opposed regulations in all those 
areas in 1982 the safety administration rolled back the bumper 
standard from 5 mph to 25 mph 
the safety administration already has work under way dealing 
with side impact crashes for cars and head restraints for light 
trucks felrice said 
he also opposed two new requirements in the bill that minivans 
and pickup trucks be built to better prevent rollovers and that 
car seats used by young children be improved he said the agency is 
already studying both problems 
the bill seems to have us begin rulemaking before we complete 
the research he said 
the safety administration established in 1966 to set vehicle 
safety standards and investigate defects came under frequent 
criticism during the reagan years by lawmakers who accused the 
agency of stifling safety initiatives 
felrice who is not a political appointee testified because the 
agency has no administrator the bush white house has said it will 
