<TEXT>
traditional italian pasta will get a special 
government qualitycontrol mark under a measure aimed at helping 
consumers distinguish it from cheaper imported mixedwheat pasta 
news reports said thursday 
according to the measure approved by the cabinet and expected 
to take effect this year foreign pastamakers will have to list 
their ingredients on packages they want to sell in italy 
even diners in restaurants will have to be notified of the type 
of pasta they are eating according to the new law 
traditional italian pasta made from durum wheat stays firm 
when cooked an important quality for those who like it al 
dente 
in july the european economic community court of justice 
overturned an italian law that barred the sale of pasta not made 
entirely with durum wheat 
the italian pasta industry has been concerned that consumers 
will be tempted to turn to the less firm mixedwheat pasta which 
costs up to 30 percent less than durum pasta and is produced in 
west germany and holland 
</TEXT>
