<TEXT>
here are significant dates in the development and 
marketing of ford motor cos mustang celebrating its silver 
anniversary this month 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
late 1960 early work began in the development of a lightweight 
sports car 
early 1962 work got under way in earnest on the vehicle 
designed to weigh less than 2500 pounds and cost less than 2500 
it went through a number of code names including allegro cougar 
no relation to the mercury car and t5 
march 9 1964 job one rolled off the line at fords dearborn 
assembly plant it weighed 2572 pounds with base sticker price of 
2368 
april 17 1964 formal introduction of the mustang 
aprilaugust 1964 firstyear sales projections of 100000 
mustangs were surpassed in four months more than 417000 mustangs 
were sold during the first year of availability 
mid1965 ford added the gt350 and gt500 to the mustang 
stable giving the car more power for the 1966 model year 
1969 model year mustang grew bulkier as muscle cars came 
into vogue during the next two model years ford introduced the 
mustang mach i boss 302 boss 429 and boss 351 
mid1970s the arab oil embargo hit and gasoline prices 
soared spelling trouble for highpowered gasgobbling cars 
mid1973 ford brought out the second generation of the car a 
smaller mustang ii for the 1974 model year during the next two 
model years the shell of the car remained virtually the same but 
ford beefed up engines offering a v8 in 1975 and a cobra ii in 
1976 
fall 1978 the third generation of the mustang was introduced 
built on the same platform as mercury cougars and ford thunderbirds 
of the day the platform is used in the 1989 mustang 
mid1981 the mustang gt was reintroduced 
fall 1985 ford added a 5liter high output engine an option 
the car still carries 
april 1989 ford quietly celebrates mustangs silver 
anniversary a caravan of 37 mustangs owned by europeans begins 
us tour on the american pony drive 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0244 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the sale of the first mustang off the assembly 
line was a mistake 
it had nothing to do with the car it was the salesman doing his 
job too well according to stanley tucker a corporate airline 
pilot now based in montreal 
they should have known better i guess tucker said in a 
telephone interview 
tucker was 32 when he was in st johns newfoundland driving by 
parsons ford on april 14 1964 there on a pedestal was a white 
mustang convertible with a black interior 
i went in and said i want to buy it tucker recalled not 
knowing that the car was in the eastern canadian province as part 
of a promotional tour a few days before the mustang officially was 
introduced 
i guess the salesman didnt realize he shouldnt sell it 
tucker said i wrote him out a check and drove the car off 
a few days later the dealer called tucker asking him to return 
the car 
i said no way ford called and they couldnt get the car 
back either he said 
i was driving that thing around for about six months in st 
johns before i ever saw another tucker said it felt great 
the car was stopping traffic on the streets people would come over 
and say what in heavens name is that 
in the united states mustangs were no strangers on the road 
the car got off to one of the hottest starts in automotive history 
topping its annual projection of 100000 sales in the first four 
months 
the appearance of the car was the thing that caught the eye of 
tucker and hundreds of thousands of other buyers in the early days 
tucker kept the original mustang for two years 
after a couple of years they ford came up with a gimmick 
and said how about trading the first car in for the millionth i 
was stupid enough to do it 
the original mustang serial number 55f08f100001 is on display 
now at the henry ford museum in dearborn mich 
tucker unrelated to automobile designer preston tucker of the 
1940s said he had no problem with the original mustang during the 
two years he owned the car during that time he put 10000 miles 
on it about half of the usual mileage open road is scarce on 
newfoundland 
what im sorry of in hindsight is getting rid of the first 
one he said if i had any brains i would have put it up on 
blocks and let it appreciate 
